  "prompt": "What is stannic hydroxide?",
  "response": "Stannic hydroxide, also known as tin(IV) hydroxide, is a chemical compound with the formula Sn(OH)\u2084. It is a hydroxide of tin in its +4 oxidation state. Stannic hydroxide is typically formed when tin(IV) salts react with bases, leading to the precipitation of a white, gelatinous solid.\n\n### Key Characteristics:\n- **Chemical Formula:** Sn(OH)\u2084\n- **Appearance:** White, gelatinous solid\n- **Solubility:** Insoluble in water\n\nWhen heated, stannic hydroxide dehydrates to form tin(IV) oxide (SnO\u2082), a process that can be represented by the following equation:\n\n\\[ \\text{Sn(OH)}_4 \\rightarrow \\text{SnO}_2 + 2\\text{H}_2\\text{O} \\]\n\n### Applications:\nStannic hydroxide and its derivative, tin(IV) oxide, are used in various industrial applications, including:\n- **Catalysis:** As a catalyst in certain chemical reactions.\n- **Ceramics and Glass:** As a component in the production of ceramics and glass.\n- **Electronics:** In the manufacture of conductive pastes and as a dielectric material in capacitors.\n\n### Safety Considerations:\nStannic hydroxide should be handled with care, as tin compounds can be toxic if ingested or inhaled. Proper safety protocols, including the use of protective equipment, should be followed when working with stannic hydroxide.",
